The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually old, they cannot work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
Women who "become" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the town.
"Men rarely suffer such but."
“We also do not isolate healthy young women, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state Burkina Faso, is taken care of in a special residence of more than one hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an informative pamphlet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” warns Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a wretched pile of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman was caught in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devourers of human souls have always represented a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, following his aunt's death, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic."
“To help, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from among the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the people arrested had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the detainees did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
Bakala’s tenant heats up with charcoal stoves and signs higher rent
The elderly and tough man crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-storey rental contracts: his, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving his sentence.
All three have just been caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of CZK 3,500 per month, the son will pay CZK 4,100 for a two-room apartment with a separate second-class kitchen starting next year.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, over whose firm he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes a move.
“Everyone says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large liberalization testing laboratory.
After New Year’s Eve it will happen with the vast majority of apartments that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rental.
That is why Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, by Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to him a machine to take number.
"Rental 2011" can be read on a light button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a small piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the big screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for settlements, insurance issues, and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the cards an increase of the rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been running for a week, so it’s starting,” the workers who are in it respond, after briefly hesitating, when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and former Bakala miners’ flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were treated loudly and clearly by the vice-president of the Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek, from the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new soil."
“They didn’t even change my goddamn bathroom plate,” the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, at the moment they come mostly retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly does not manage to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for rent in 2011," the employee of the window estimates.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, an independent judge must settle the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed that is possible and completely compliant with the law," RPG warns in its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of the employees of RPG Byty and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,” he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“The current rents do not yet cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klima<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, adding that the careless state of the community fund that angers the tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in rentals in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that highlights in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
“In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 CZK per month per square meter,” the display reads.
Only increased by 38% the rental of 400 floors of the portfolio of RPG.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, 19.66 kroner per square meter," RPG said.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale from four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money of the hike of the rent (see the graph) again in the floors, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the hike agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need nursery
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything proper to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio came numerous well-known buildings from Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini daycare.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow the architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity leave.
Together with the possibility to enjoy a reduced schedule, the daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers as part of its social program.
The builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-nursery was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-garden is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a dotation of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-garden in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the Economy Rating company contributed to the submission of the financing application.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present throughout the day for their care. The daycare centre currently accommodates children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-store", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten program are comparable to the usual preschool program.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach English.
The class has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive when they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colours, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all are typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twisting of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door trims, viewfinders and signs.
Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street Passeig de Gràcia, arose from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of making a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project emerged ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá and Güell Park, in which other parts of it can be found.
Because of its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion dubbed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building conceal religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its inclination of forty-five degrees may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the building rules of the time at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the reconstruction planned were so vague that, two years later, upon its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it asked to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, quite the contrary: only fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, of six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí’s reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors brings maximum light to all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most crowded apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
