How to choose the mattress and the bed frame: women and men are looking for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really confers its quality to a good bed is the surface for lying down, that is, the mattress and the spring.
Above all, they must complement each other perfectly so that they adapt to the specific users.
During the election come into play numerous elements, including the weight, height, health status and sex of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and bed base is located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat" more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them more frequently.
If the channels in the center are not properly aerated and, above, they are on a firm basis, they keep moisture inside.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, hard surface.
“Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who have problems with the nervous system, so they receive bad information from the joints and the skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in quilted furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem anymore, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelastic.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not turn like after a hard game.
It just sleeps better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to your height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example for singles, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk towards your elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert from Cechu <0xC4><0x8D>alouník<0xC5><0xAF> to decorater<0xC5><0xAF>, who has been specializing in the problem of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for many years.
In double rooms, each needs its own bed base and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the frames at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with spring interior a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
“When you touch it with your hand or settle on the mattress, you certainly shouldn’t notice the springs,” warns Helena Prokopova.
Each mattress requires a certain type of bed base.
The fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and you can not wash your cover, which today is often done.
And, since we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat every night, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime warranty.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, the sellers give advice: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, carefully take care of cleaning and washing the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers are currently manufactured with a zipper closure throughout its perimeter, so when opening them they are left in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a bedspread, do you have a firm board?
Never! Never!
At most for the beds designed for overnight visits.
However, it should make (if you don’t already have them) vent holes in the board and should be used with a mattress with springs on the inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (like the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulatable sheet beds containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used, although it is always better to have a bed with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lower back are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated.
Hinged sheet beds should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the sheets that allows pressing or even tilting the sheets in such a way that they "surround" perfectly the shoulders during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "male", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are springs with cross structure or tablets with the so-called multi-torsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that, even if you use the right mattress and bed base, if you use a bad pillow (large and "muffled"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should hold the head and the corners can only reach up to the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can be relaxed.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder pad or softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, increasingly, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are fashionable.
Petroleum-based raw materials, from which polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soybeans.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1>í<0xC4><0x8D>ek of the Tropico Plus company.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" with plant extracts of breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women prefer to "warm" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel more warmth.
Favorites right now?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with a structure of adapted cells, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold foam and viscoelastic stiffnesses allow to manufacture mattresses from various areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as health means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and sommiers.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is free.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cell structure and high density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
It initially emerged as material for NASA, because during the takeoffs astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents use people tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for tracking vehicles, can also track the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old girl Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka and began to learn about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
“We all try to tell each other that this is not about spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy happening,” said Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
“I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone’s purse without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases.”
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,” adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková warns about the fact that, if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled.”
“In the past, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device,” says Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
“If it is a prepared kidnapping, the perpetrator will practically always check if the child is carrying any kind of electronic device that can reveal his location.”
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices expands, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be made with a lot of publicity."
“In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert <0xC4><0x8C>ech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even in the event that, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can serve as a help.
"You can configure the device to regularly send the position after a certain period."
"If it suffers damage, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question."
“The most expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stands still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says <0xC4><0x8C>ech.
In his view, such a service can be obtained even with smartphones with navigation, on which only special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a similar size to a box of matches or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, that’s why devices that look like a digital clock are currently being tested.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device."
"Or identify it after a while, which can save the police time," he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to set off explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of wick to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the wick is two years, four at the most.
The army bought the wick for explosives from the STV Group, a. s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of wick per year.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnicians of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that, in such a case, such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives should be carried out every year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Minister of Defense Alexandr Vondr nor army captain Vlastimil Picek wanted exemptions.
Only in this way could the army be justified in spending sixty kilometers of wick.
Such a length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even so, the army would have sufficient stocks for more than ten years.
If on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (including adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade recently complained personally to Minister Vondra because they say that they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even shooting practices are limited for the sake of money.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
“I also don’t understand why they repeatedly buy us such amounts of wick.”
“But it’s their decision and they’ll certainly know why they’re acting like that.”
“For us, the military is a good customer that we, as a company, try to satisfy,” admits STV Group sales director Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick by also saying that he will have stockpiles of this "ammo" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD> of STV Group says that the wick has a service life of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, it got a discount.
“They cost us 60% less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” said Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, a spokesman for the Defense Ministry’s procurement center.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of police pyrotechnics, who dispose of World War II ammunition or ammunition left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only for the right amount to exhaust the ammunition before its useful life ends.
They decided for safety reasons for the pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The Ministry is already struggling to finish tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the Czechoslovakian army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: you will have to remove hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
