Families will have to pay additional expenses of several hundred kroner per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, larger rents.
As a result, from January onwards, families will have to withdraw several hundred kroner a month more than they do now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by about 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 kroner more a year than now.
However, major electricity suppliers cut prices, as support for the production of energy from renewable sources, particularly photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas is moderately expensive, especially at a time when heating is used the most and therefore the higher the consumption.
In this case, they should also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are rising across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about 50 kroner per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 kroner per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially in case the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, the Pragueers will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will continue to be among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
Prices for 450,000 rented flats in Prague, where the regulation will end in January, can increase considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns in <0xC3><0x9A>stí nad Labem around 2,500 floors, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will bring to court those who disagree with the new rental.
Regulated rentals, which benefit residents of around 300,000 floors, could increase next year by as much as 10%.
The young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in mode, because it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
Those are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors encountering such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk."
"Strong alcoholic beverages are now the fashion," Lud<0xC4><0x9B>k Pelikán, head of pediatrics at Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice Hospital in central Bohemia, told Právo.
"When they manage to get a bottle from their father in the cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage that it lightens up with juice and doesn’t smell so much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
“In some cases, they use brandy that they picked up at home,” adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, thirteen and fourteen-year-old drinkers often appear in hospitals.
Prior to Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where she has been working since this year, she worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to check in maybe four times."
"She started at the age of 12, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy," the department's doctor said of the case.
"He was at the Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother wasn't surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours," he said.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot speak properly of dependency.
"Alcoholic is a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year at the pediatric clinic in Motol, forty drunk children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the ambulance medical examination, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply meet after school and drink liquor, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: Halloween, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad notes or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
“On Halloween, I saw up to seven drunken children in admissions at the same time,” adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is prevented by injecting a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"These are much better off, because after the hectic night, they get up well and it doesn't hurt at all."
“They’re only confused about where they are,” Pelikán says, adding that patients often lose their mood at least when they see the expenses they’ve generated.
Ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a room for severe patients can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when in the visit I tell them directly to the children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend all summer in a job for young people so that you would earn enough to pay that night," adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for the costs of treatment, does not in the case of drinking children.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Defense Ministry replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the aircraft Casa - EADS is located.
This is the first time that such a device has been in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
For the time being, they were only abroad for internship or demonstration flights.
It is the two-seater version L-159T1, which until now was used by the Czech army and which was still in a flying state.
The remaining three aircraft are the L-159 single-seat aircraft.
These are still preserved in Aer Vodochody and the intermediary of the sale, the company Omnipol, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peje<0xC5><0xA1>k, of the defense press department, said it was not yet known when the aircraft would be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the long-repaired aircraft, with no additional investments or contributions from the Ministry."
“The L-159T1 two-seaters were exchanged in their current state,” Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek told Právo.
He added that the army does not run out of two-seat aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed with Aer Vodochody a contract for the amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seat aircraft.
One of the new aircraft has already been received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, EADS has pledged that the aircraft will be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly indicates that EADS is the company that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and that they will serve for pilot practices from NATO countries."
“It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how they will be used in this framework,” says Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek.
The newspaper Hospodá<0xC5><0x99>ské noviny published early that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defense did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense direction states that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 abroad.
The Czech army has acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already sued the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because it should choose aircraft by conducting a European tender and not contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa aircraft and the last one should arrive at the Prague airport of Kbely in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have a longer index than the ring index are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length may constitute a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other detrimental factors, such as family health problems, Eeles said.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the annular finger.
They had the same odds of getting prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under the age of 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he knows the study, but does not think the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "completely demonstrated."
