Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is the surprise pick in the Revelation Artist category.
Act at the request of a president and possibly people will notice you.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old bass player and jazz singer personally selected by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, was one of the Grammys’ surprises this year with a top-level nomination in the Best New Artist category.
Considering that Spalding has been an acclaimed jazz figure since his 2008 album "Esperanza", the nomination is thought-provoking, but respects the Grammys rules that he must be an artist who has not released more than three albums before recording the one that "determines the public identity of that artist".
His ambitious 2010 album "Chamber Music Society" undoubtedly made a breakthrough and, given his lightweight and enjoyable vocal style, as well as great skill with pop, funk and Latin rhythms influences, he can at least draw a distinction between Spalding and the path to Norah Jones's success in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammy voters, who have lately stood in the category of jazz.
In the remaining categories, Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio’s “Historicity,” an exciting and magnificent record that was a favorite last year.
Iyer's competitors include veteran saxophonist James Moody with "Moody 4B" and keyboardist John Beasley for "Positootly."
