Before the spring of this year, he returned to the design table as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of internal debate and disagreement, was finally backed by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially exits bankruptcy in the coming weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies will receive multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will get a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper’s companies, which have been raising $375,000 per month for their company management services, will receive a “successful fee” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production on MGM, which premiered only one film this year, and gathered an annual slate of seven or eight films to be released in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on “The Hobbit,” along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to arrange a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to fund its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18 percent of MGM’s debt, had been trying to fix a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
