A more moderate side of law enforcement is being promoted in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin stepped into a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, China’s corpulent urban order policemen, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and propensity for violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of viewers.
"Firm!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls who barely passed adolescence in white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to draw attention.
Four pairs of perfectly lined black shoes.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
“Personally, I think they look normal,” Mr. Tang said, dismissively.
“The models are beautiful.”
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a blue supposedly more attractive.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a dysfunctional snack cart, and watched it frowning constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, feminine side.
Sadly, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s insignificant respect for these city squadrons.
And for good reason, the critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, Hubei Province inspectors beat to death a passerby after using his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted online, describing how to effectively flog criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon street vendor suffered brain damage after a brawl with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded “a really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district solicited through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News asked whether the women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district notice called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features."
They should have a height above average, greater than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is compulsory.
Officials said the work was too physically arduous for women over the age of 25.
“Your image is the important thing,” an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
“First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc.”
Then comes the temperament “and the inner qualities.”
Female chengguans are like vases, he said, adding, “beside being vases, they will have other responsibilities.”
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city administration office, is not eager to endorse that description.
But he noted that height requirements were standard in many Chinese job postings for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
Whether this means being handsome is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the disabled or disfigured should not be presented.
“We can’t allow a lame person or a humpback to come and work here,” Mr. Zheng said.
"His image wouldn't be good."
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, with his red cheeks and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn’t believe the accent on her appearance is sexist, she said.
