Red Bull triumphs in F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
Software designs real-time car improvements.
Since Red Bull broke into the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select world of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first nobody took into consideration the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the final straight of the championship everyone bet on the victory of Fernando Alonso’s Ferrari.
Without disregarding the skill as a driver of the eventual champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor the ability of the Renault engine that powers his car, in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from the high car competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computing instrument has been used to design assembly lines of manufacturing plants around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding failures and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan’s most celebrated commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains that the use of this computer tool in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and carry out “in a few hours, almost in real time”, the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during the races and in the tests.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four vehicle improvements during each season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications to the bolides.
The manager of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all the elements of the Red Bull cars with the exception of the engine, which is the sole responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can be taken from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this madness of technological refinement is the $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its cars in a town about 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "high secrecy".
The team for this task amounts to 580 people, including its two drivers, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The Red Bull Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, are hidden other protagonists whose competition is invaluable and their notoriety null.
The factory’s chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be said that R&D advances in trucks contributed 50% of the wins and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and the technology adds up to 85% of the success, while the pilots contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettels or Webbers will never be replaced by computers as "they are unpredictable gladiators."
