Pakistan's nuclear program raises serious concern in the United States
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at “a faster pace than any other country.”
WikiLeaks leaks confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns raised in Washington by the Pakistani nuclear program.
Aside from the enlightening and juicy details they offer about the content of the talks and the thoughts of U.S. diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on atomic security, instead of going up, “decreases,” and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons “at a faster rate than any other country in the world.”
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but remain stored by components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
As Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson puts it in a report ahead of then-National Security Advisor James Jones’ visit: “The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumoured dispersion of nuclear materials, and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials.”
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is seen, not only by the US, but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to keep guard.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given falling educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people working in nuclear or missile programs," Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his U.S. counterparts.
The novelty of the documentation leaked by Julian Assange’s portal is the ever-decreasing cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and the high Pakistani pace of nuclear weapons production.
An embassy dispatch in May, which called communication with Pakistan "frustrating," said: "Transparency is often non-existent; offers of aid remain unanswered or are discarded."
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world."
Ambassador Patterson also urged Washington, during a visit by the head of the army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make "very clear" to the person responsible that "the Pakistani army must end tacit support for terrorist groups."
The Chase of the WikiLeaks Chief
Obama appoints a senior counter-terrorism official to prevent further leaks.
Interpol is issuing a red alert in order to track the movements and locate Assange wherever he is.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated maze where it is difficult to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a “red alert” to “locate and track the movements” of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
Also, it is not new, but dates from November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million U.S. diplomatic documents but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
Mark Stephens, the lawyer for WikiLeaks’ creator, said: “Police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.
It was on the 20th when the international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
All 188 Interpol countries have indications of identifying or locating Assange “in view of his provisional arrest and extradition.”
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, according to the organization, do consider the so-called free-way notification network to proceed with an arrest - which must be undertaken by the national police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The movement has outraged Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder has been willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities by videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor in his case, whom they compare to the mythical Lavrenty Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s head of security.
"This looks like a hunt, not a legal persecution," the letter said.
As the world searches for him - and from Australia his mother defends his son's innocence - Assange is still unknown, but not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview with Time magazine’s editor via Skype, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering U.S. diplomats to spy on the U.N. in violation of international treaties that the U.S. has signed, he should resign,” he said.
