Obama himself has commissioned a senior counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks of documents.
President Barack Obama’s spokesman’s attempt to downplay Assange contrasts with views proclaimed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Peter King, the congressman who will preside over the National Security Committee in the lower house from January, has asked the State Department to consider including WikiLeaks on the list of terrorist organizations "to intervene and its funds and pursue anyone who gives them any contribution or help."
Still further has gone Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, who has had to retract after saying Assange should “be killed.”
“Obama should make it a target and use a drone or something.”
Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and a potential presidential candidate, did not apologize.
“Whoever in the government leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything other than execution would be too gentle a punishment,” he said.
