Rivers under extreme surveillance
Several waterways are being closely monitored due to heavy rainfall that has been recorded in several regions of the province since Tuesday.
On Wednesday afternoon there was a landslide in Shawinigan, Mauricie.
As a preventive measure, two houses have been evacuated.
At night, another landslide occurred at Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in Lanaudière.
A road sank.
From Tuesday to Wednesday night, several regions recorded heavy rainfall, between 40 and 70 millimeters of rain.
An additional 20 to 40 millimeters are expected from now until Thursday night, depending on the region.
The sectors north of the river and in the Outaouais valley were the most affected.
They could receive up to a total of 100 millimeters of rain.
Since these precipitations add to the melting of snow that had already accumulated in certain sectors, it is feared that several rivers will overflow.
On Wednesday night, the Quebec Civil Security unit issued alerts for the Ouareau and Achigan rivers in Lanaudière.
The rivers of the north, in Saint-Jérôme in the Laurentians, and of the Chêne in Lotbinière, have already caused flooding in the past and are under surveillance.
In the Lanaudière region, heavy rainfall has caused some lakes to overflow in Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
In Saint-Calixte, heavy rains have dragged a temporary bridge.
As a preventive measure, 10 residences have been evacuated.
In the Outaouais, the overflow of certain lakes has led to the closure of several tracks, in particular in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The Civil Security unit remains on alert and closely monitors the situation, security adviser Annik Bouchard said.
The Quebec Flood Forecast Center, meanwhile, issued announcements Wednesday communicating the strong floods of several rivers, in particular the Maskinongé, the Assumption, the Ouareau, the Achigan, the Batiscan and the Loup.
Dupont is partially to blame.
Quebec radio presenter Stéphane Dupont has suffered a setback before the Canadian Broadcasting Standards Council (CBSC) over controversial statements regarding welfare and Haitians, as well as his rude language on the radio.
The CCNR considers that Mr. Dupont and his team of CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their opinion, but certain statements contained "inaccurate information about social assistance, an unduly negative representation of Haitians and rude language that should not be used in broadcasts broadcast during the day."
The Council has also indicated that discussions on suicide, including the disclosure of the names of two persons who committed suicide, do not violate broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints regarding comments made on broadcasts broadcast between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was issued following a complaint by the Quebec Common Front of People Receiving Social Assistance.
The group complained that the amounts mentioned in the broadcast were incorrect.
Presenters should report reliable data and not one that leads to deception.
Regarding suicide, the featured Stéphane Dupont had stated that suicide was an act of cowardice.
Most members of the Committee had concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life ' s problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes in question of 'Dupont le midi' have dealt with a sensitive subject in an equitable and appropriate manner."
In this respect, therefore, any blame has been dismissed.
The latest litigation concerned statements made after the Haiti earthquake.
At that time, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had starred in a media confrontation that had provoked numerous reactions.
The CHOI presenter stated that he had not made any donations to help the Haitians because he could not know for sure if the needy were really going to receive the money.
The Committee considers that these comments are not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already served my three-day suspension up there."
"My file has been clean for a year and a half," the presenter said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the issuance of rude language.
In any case, the radio station CHOI-FM has collaborated "even more than required".
The consequences will be minimal for the broadcaster, which must, among other things, announce the decisions once in the hours of highest audience within three days.
A King of Kung Fu in Montreal
The Algerian-born Montrealer Nacereddine Zemmal has had an extremely peculiar journey.
The athlete, who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and and thai box, climbs the tatamis and rings of the world in search of new challenges.
“I started practicing martial arts like kung-fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria,” explained Zemmal, who has lived in the metropolis since 2008 to advance at the professional level.
"In my case, I'm looking for fights everywhere because, for those who don't enjoy the ground-based game of mixed martial arts, there are few competitions in North America."
The athlete, who works as a security officer and as an employee of the company UPS, has recently given bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) Amateur World Championships, held from October 23 to 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
“I’ve won in the full contact kickboxing and Thai boxing categories,” he explained.
“I am currently preparing to participate in the San Shou World Cup in China.”
“They will invite athletes who have finished in the top four places in the last world championship in each category.”
"In 2009, I won the bronze medal in Toronto."
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished in eighth place."
"In 2007, in China, I finished the tournament in fifth place, but I reached third place in Toronto in 2009," he added.
“The interesting thing is that I’ve been progressing in every competition.”
“At this point, I’ll be the first one this time or next year!”
San shou or sanda is a discipline originally from China in which it is allowed to strike with fists and feet, as well as throw opponents to the ground.
Clashes are originally held on a platform and, less frequently, in a ring.
The most famous boxer in this type of combat is the American of Vietnamese origin Cung Le, widely recognized in the world of martial arts.
Although Nacer Zemmal only has to maintain a competition in his career, he will undoubtedly attend the great tournament "King of Sanda", the Super Bowl of kung-fu.
“This competition is the most notorious and prestigious in China,” explains the friendly boy.
“It’s like the equivalent of the Lumpinee stadium (the largest stadium in Thailand).”
"It's been an incredible experience."
Zemmal has won his first fight, in the semifinals of his category (80 kg), but lost in the final.
“The one who has won me is a real professional,” he says.
"There are four competitors per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg)."
"The winners of the semifinals face each other in the final of their category."
“Then the champions in each category face off to crown a single champion, the king of kung-fu.”
450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has awarded direct contracts worth $450 million to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without prior tender the most important contract, the project management contract, for a sum of 295 million.
The consortium, called Énergie gérance, was created in 2004 following the decision of Hydro-Québec to entrust to the private sector its responsibility to manage this important hydroelectric project of 5 billion dollars.
At the beginning of 2005, the Énergie gérance consortium obtained the lucrative contract without prior public tendering.
For the Quebec Party, the use of consortia of companies poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and cause a rise in prices.
“This is a new method of collusion and eliminating competition.”
“In other words, people, instead of doing it in secret, are now doing it openly,” Quebec Party MP Sylvain Simard said at a press conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can be benefited in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, firmly denying that there had been any collusion with this contract.
"I'm starting to get tired," he protested, saying the PQ had acted "dishonestly" and "lack of rigor."
He pointed out that "the least" would be for the PQ to apologize.
The formula of consortia is a common practice throughout the world.
Typically, this is an alliance with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
The works have already begun and will last until 2012.
In any case, the contract has been awarded without competition; it has been a negotiation.
In addition, the consortia formula has ceased to be the exception to the norm in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the formula of the consortiums in the technical advisory sector is being investigated in the Government.
A quick look at the Quebec trade register identifies more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
In this way, the company Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Genivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal entity, namely Dessau.
With regard to the Énergie gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that "the James Bay territory responds to a particular workforce dynamic and Hydro-Québec has responded specifically to it since the 1970s".
The great head of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has given an explanation that has highlighted the fact that the project management contract has been awarded directly.
"If you respond to a tender and there are few participants, your prices will be higher."
“You have two options: you can get in touch with the actors in the sector and tell them: we will negotiate a satisfactory deal and at a good price.”
"However, the idea is that what matters is not the price, but the competition of the people," said Mr. Laporte.
The contract awarded to the Énergie gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts worth more than $50,000 obtained by the Quebec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or the SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following the verification, Le Devoir identified 109 technical advisory contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to companies or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has won 22 contracts, Genivar 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account its participation in Énergie gérance.
All contracts were negotiated.
In total, they amount to $449.783,344, including the Énergie gérance contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard has implied that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "good acquaintances of the Liberal Party of Quebec".
Minister Normandeau has dropped that the PQ is also linked to these companies, which "fund" it, before specifying that it is more about their leaders.
Responsible consumption barometer. The label "green" does not inspire confidence
More ecological, but deeply skeptical.
The Quebec consumer hardly trusts the actors of sustainable development, as well as fair trade brands or organic certificates to guide their choices.
According to the Responsible Consumption Barometer, whose first results were published yesterday, the situation is even worse: the consumer is immersed in a media universe where messages that defend a more responsible consumption are pulverized, but regrets the lack of reliable information and considers that it even slows down their commitment.
Even if consumption of so-called “socially responsible” products has increased in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those who try to sell them.
Two-thirds of them say, in fact, that they do not trust the environmental commitment of companies or the environmental advertising of the same, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatory of responsible consumption of the University of Sherbrooke.
Another conclusion: half of consumers question the reliability of official certificates that carry the so-called fair products, as well as the credibility of products and brands that carry labels indicating that they are "eco-responsible", notes the Barometer.
Similarly, only 14.6% of Quebecers take politicians' speeches on this issue seriously.
In any case, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this consumption sector, currently supported by about a third of Quebec consumers.
In fact, gaps and the questionable nature of the information cause 46% of consumers to discard this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers also say they are suspicious of the supposed returns of the ecological products or services they are trying to sell.
On the other hand, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, especially, changed the brand of one or more products to respect their convictions.
61% have given priority to shopping in stores in their neighborhood and have preferred to buy food products grown in their region, says the Barometer.
Greener and more responsible (the responsible consumption index has reached 64 points out of a maximum of 100 this year), the Homo consumus of Quebec loves to take the place of the king of recycling who tries to reduce its impact on the environment by worrying about the protection of fauna.
However, according to the Barometer, this social awareness seems to be outside the doors (of your car): in 2010, only 28% of Quebecers indicated that they have used public transport or have shared a car to defend their environmental principles.
In addition, 39.1% of the participants in this comprehensive behavioral survey, which has just completed its first edition, support the use of bicycles and walking.
A loan for the state to recover eXcentris
The Government of Quebec, which has been asked to commit itself financially to the recovery of the eXcentris cinema complex by the Société Angus and the Parallèle, agrees to cooperate, but only by means of a loan.
The Société de développement Angus and the Parallèle, who were hoping for a $7 million donation from the Ministry of Culture to repurchase from Daniel Langlois the eXcentris film complex on Saint-Laurent Boulevard and return it to its true cinematic vocation, have not obtained what they were asking for.
The Government has agreed to be involved in the matter, but on its own terms.
Instead of the expected donation, the Government of Quebec is proposing a loan whose amount would, in fact, be lower than the initial expectations; this could constitute a viable solution under advantageous conditions, at least in the opinion of certain public employees.
Quebec had already rejected an initial action plan and a $12.8 million application last spring, but applications have since been revised downward.
The president of the Société de développement des entreprises culturelles (SODEC), François Macerola, who leads the eXcentris dossier, submitted a proposal and an action plan to Minister St-Pierre.
He sent you a final report a dozen days ago.
However, SODEC received a counter-proposal from the cabinet on Tuesday.
The Parallèle and Angus have until December 31 to respond to it.
In any case, it seems that the hypothesis of a state donation should be completely discarded.
Recall that the Quebec Association of Cinema Owners and Film Complexes opposed a direct investment by the State to support the recovery of eXcentris, arguing that the Ministry of Culture should not finance real estate projects, since it has not done so with other cinemas.
On the other hand, several representatives of the sector do call for considerable financial aid.
Daniel Langlois, the owner of the complex, has for ten years carried the burden of the auteur cinema in its premises of the complex, after financing its own construction, which could justify a repeal by the Treasury Council.
The lack of independent film theaters is evident in Montreal and eXcentris had been able to retain its clientele.
The company Angus and Parallèle, led by Christian Yaccarini, are for their part promoting a private financing campaign, hoping to raise $ 700,000 to pave the way for the acquisition.
Since spring 2009, only one of these rooms, the Parallèle, continues to screen films on eXcentris.
The goal of the future buyers is to reopen the three rooms on February 27, screening Xavier Beauvois's beautiful film "Des hommes et des dieux".
However, Christian Yaccarini has not contacted Le Devoir again and we do not know what he and his group think of the downward proposals they have received.
The veil of complex Canada is lifted...
The new U.S. diplomatic cables leaked by WikiLeaks reveal what the U.S. sees as the Canadians’ complex with respect to the Americans, but at the same time reflect the latter’s feeling of superiority to Canada.
U.S. diplomats are surprised that Canadian voters do not think about Canada-U.S. relations when they go to vote and believe that President Obama’s visit has helped the Conservative government get its budget approved in 2009!
The four new communications between the U.S. embassy in Ottawa and Washington that have been made public yesterday offer rather juicy details than really substantial content.
A cable from September 22, 2008, that is, during the full federal election campaign, tells how far the United States does not enter into the issues debated by the political leaders.
This caused great surprise to the American ambassador sent to Ottawa, David Wilkins.
Mr Wilkins gives some explanations of this situation.
“Perhaps political leaders are conditioned by an inferiority complex virtually inherent in Canadians when it comes to dealing with daily domestic issues, rather than leaving such an election to the United States (as during the 1988 free trade campaign),” he writes.
Accordingly, he concludes, the United States is “the proverbial elephant of this choice: ubiquitous, but potentially too dangerous to talk about.”
The ambassador has even more trouble understanding this "deafening silence" because the two countries maintain intense political and economic relations.
“Logically, the ability of a candidate, a party and, even more so, the head of a party to manage these essential relationships should be a key factor that voters should think about when voting.”
This feeling of importance can also be seen in the cable sent on January 22, 2009 by Terry Breese, the Ottawa business manager, to prepare President Barack Obama for his first visit to Ottawa.
“His trip will help ensure the government’s survival during the confidence vote in early February on the federal budget, whereby Canada will for the first time record a deficit in the last decade due to a $30 to $40 billion recovery plan,” wrote Mr. Breese.
Nowhere is it mentioned that the government had to extend Parliament before Christmas to prevent it from being replaced by the coalition or that the opposition parties conditioned their survival to the quality of the proposed recovery plan.
Another January 2008 communication signed by Ambassador Wilkins warns Washington about the increasingly negative image conveyed by the drama series broadcast on CBC in the United States.
The ambassador is concerned about the broadcast of Border, Little Mosque on the Prairie, Intelligence and H2O, in which unsubtle references are made to Maher Arar, to the "No-Fly-List" or even to the kidnappings for the CIA to carry out vigorous interrogations.
Another cable says that, during her first bilateral meeting, Hillary Clinton asked her French counterpart Bernard Kouchner if Europe would be willing to host some Guantanamo prisoners.
Mr. Kouchner replied that yes, but that it depended "on each case".
At the end of the meeting, they wrote “has delivered a document to the Secretary of State in relation to Omar Khadr, a 15-year-old Muslim of Canadian origin.”
"The Secretary agreed to review the file."
Finally, we can mention that the moods have warmed in relation to the WikiLeaks site.
Tom Flanagan, a former adviser very close to Stephen Harper, declared on CBC radio that the person responsible for this massive leak should be "murdered".
Mike Huckabee in the United States.
A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate before 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of concrete major projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluorescent compact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to lower global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should still be decreased to stabilize, before 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from spiraling out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced even more than twice.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in one hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above all, they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have expressed reservations about compact fluorescent bulbs, as they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the main source of mercury emission on the planet are not compact fluorescent bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted by incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save $1 billion a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it $2.5 billion.
Ivory Coast Eagerly Expects Election Results Announcement
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has called for the "immediate" publication of the results of the presidential elections in Côte d'Ivoire, given that the deadlines set have expired.
"The Secretary-General stresses the need for the independent electoral commission to complete its work and announce the provisional results immediately," a spokesman for the UN chief said.
“Calls on all Ivorian parties and institutions to demonstrate their sense of responsibility and refrain from any initiative until the provisional results are announced.”
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the election commission has allowed Wednesday's deadline to pass midnight without the results being released, three days after Sunday's poll.
About forty minutes before the deadline, the president of the CIS had told television that the commission was "continuing to work" to announce the results.
On Wednesday, demands have multiplied in the world for the CIS to finally proclaim the name of the winner of the second round between the outgoing Laurent Gbagbo and his opponent Alassane Ouattara.
However, Gbagbo's side counts on the Constitutional Council's annulment of the "fraudulent" votes in the north, in the hands of the former rebellion of the New Forces (FN) since the failed coup d'etat of September 2002.
Pascal Affi N'Guessan, campaign director of the Ivorian president, said the FN's intimidation of voters in the north of the country had deterred supporters of the outgoing president from going to vote.
The entire election could be annulled if the Constitutional Council accepts the complaints filed by Gbagbo.
However, Gbagbo's opponents consider that the country's highest court is not neutral, since it is led by Paul Yao N'Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, a northerner who denies any relationship with the former rebels, has deemed the delay in publishing the results "unacceptable" and has asked Gbagbo to respect them, but has not gone so far as to claim victory.
His allies claim that Gbagbo blocks the publication of the results because he knows he has lost and that submitting a complaint to the Constitutional Council after having prevented the electoral commission from disseminating the results would be illegal.
The second round of the presidential elections, on Sunday, should have been the icing on the cake for the process of reunification and reconciliation of a country divided in two for years.
The United Nations on Wednesday warned Ivory Coast’s political class that they could be held responsible for possible acts of violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished in the first round, on 31 October, with 38% of the vote against 32% for Alassane Ouattara, who publicly received the support of former President Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
The unemployment rate remains stable in France in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Organization (ILO), the unemployment rate in France has remained stable at 9.3% in continental territory (9.7% taking into account the overseas departments), as indicated by the data corrected with the seasonal variations (CVE) provisional published Thursday by the INSEE.
The number of unemployed remains at 2,631,000 in mainland France.
The data of the second quarter have been confirmed, 9.3% of the active population in continental territory and 9.7% with the DOM.
In one year, the unemployment rate has increased by 0.1 points.
Overall, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter but want to work, whether or not they are available within two weeks to work and whether or not they are looking for work.
The situation of young people present in the labour market has continued to worsen, with a further increase in the unemployment rate to 24.2% in mainland France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in one year), 25% including the DOM.
During the third quarter, 637,000 young people between the ages of 15 and 24 were unemployed in the ILO sense.
For its part, there has been a slight increase in unemployment among the elderly, up to 6.4% in mainland France (+0.2 points both in three months and in one year), that is, 482,000 people over 50 years of age, a figure that amounts to 6.6% with the DOM.
Unemployment has been stable only among people aged 25 to 49, with 8.3% in mainland France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
The INSEE has not published the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy over its calculation methods.
Eurostat, the European Union's statistics agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October, after 9.9% in September.
Alexandre Guérini investigated and arrested
Alexandre Guérini, 53, a manager of waste treatment companies and brother of the PS president of the General Council of Bouches-du-Rhône, is being investigated and has been imprisoned in the Luynes prison, near Aix-en-Provence, as part of an investigation into allegedly fraudulent public procurement.
Alexandre Guérini is being investigated for abuse of social property, embezzlement of funds and public goods, cover-up, active corruption, trafficking in influences and possession of ammunition, according to his lawyer.
"Alexandre Guérini will fight and answer all the questions that the magistrate asks him, not ghosts."
“It’s easy to prosecute him for a multitude of reprehensible acts, it’s another matter to prove them,” his lawyer, Florence Rault, told AFP before her client’s appearance.
Mr. Guérini, brother of the leader of the PS in the department, Jean-No<0xC3><0xAB>l Guérini, has wanted to transmit through his lawyers to the judge, before his appearance, a document to explain himself.
On Wednesday night, they began investigating and also imprisoned one of their close relatives, Philippe Rapezzi.
According to his lawyer, Mr. Lucien Simon, all his client has done is deal with the landfills he has to manage.
As for the allocation of contracts or the destination of the funds related to their execution, he knows nothing about it, according to counsel Simon.
As part of this case, Daniel Pinna, former director general of the services of the urban agglomeration of Aubagne, has also been under investigation since Wednesday for embezzlement and complicity, but he has been released on parole and is prohibited from meeting with the protagonists of the case.
"My client has been able to explain all the facts that have reproached him."
“The investigating magistrate took into account the explanations and released him,” said his lawyer, Yann Arnoux.
On the night of Tuesday to Wednesday they interrogated four other people and released them, under judicial control in the case of two of them, according to the deputy prosecutor of the Republic, Michel Raffin.
Michel Karabadjakian, deputy general manager of the property of Marseille Provence Métropole (MPM), has been charged with “influence trafficking and passive corruption”.
Two officials from the agglomeration of Aubagne, Michèle Duval and Christophe Bringuier, have been questioned for "theft and embezzlement of public goods by a person dedicated to the public service" and for "complicity in the embezzlement of public funds", respectively.
Finally, Alexandre Guérini’s partner, Jeannie Peretti, is being investigated for “cover-up of abuse of social goods.”
Among the people who have confronted Mr Guérini is Stéphane Brunengo-Girard, recently imprisoned in a parallel case of fraudulent public procurement in Corsica.
Investigators suspect that their societies have served to launder the capital of the great banditry.
The investigation is being carried out within the framework of several judicial instructions initiated against X in April 2009 following the receipt of anonymous communications, of course fraud in the award of public contracts, in particular in the waste sector.
A source close to the investigation notes that the investigations focus especially on the conditions of allocation and operation of a landfill in La Ciotat, which collects waste from Aubagne, as well as other cities in the urban community of Marseille (MPM).
Clotilde Reiss: The Elysee has exaggerated Syria’s mediation
For more than ten months, between July 2009 and May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher detained in Iran for “espionage”, has been in the grip of the public in France, has alerted diplomacy and has accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of U.S. diplomats.
The US documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal certain unknown aspects of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysee has explained its strategy to the Americans to the point of giving them advice on managing their own “hostage” crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman did not come in exchange for the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detainee in France and wanted by US justice for smuggling materials for the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they reveal the harsh reality of how the French presidency tried to manipulate the media to give the idea that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad had played an essential role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
Actually, he didn't do anything.
A diplomatic telegram drawn up on 12 August 2009 in Paris bears the title "Iran: French comments on how to handle hostage-taking cases".
The Elysee Councillor for Strategic Affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, speak with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the following to repatriate their own citizens held by force in Iran.
“Make noise,” they say, “continuously release” in the media the words “fundamental human rights,” “innocence,” “immediate release.”
All to shame the Iranian regime, careful of its image.
“When the Iranians ask you to stop, do it even more often.”
Because, once the attempts at negotiation by discrete channels have been exhausted, "silence will solve nothing", the Iranians are "experts in delaying maneuvers".
Mr Richier adds that the detention of foreigners is "a usual Iranian tactic: the taking of hostages for political blackmail."
He announces that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (which will take place on August 16, the day on which she will take refuge in the French embassy) "will require the payment of the Iranians of a large amount of money" (230,000 euros of reward).
In addition, he points out that the Elysee anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will increase".
The Iranians could “in the near future arrest another of the nearly 1,800 French citizens living in Iran,” he says.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss is released from prison after 12 days, but is blocked in Iran.
The following information is being disseminated: the Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition is requested by the United States for illicit trafficking of sensitive electronic material to Iran, has been released in Paris by a decision of a judge.
The U.S. embassy, like many observers, doubt this strange coincidence.
For Washington, which is looking into Iran’s clandestine material procurement networks for the nuclear program, the release of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Did France accept an exchange?
Free the Iranian in exchange for the French?
