Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every dossier created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news from public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucian) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The whistleblower is lazy, just as the head of the secret services (if he could not be, what do I know, editor of Libération) is lazy (or has little appetite), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as that published in Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since the Second World War and since the heads of states can call each other on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into espionage centers.
Any spectator who watches research films knows it perfectly, we just pretend that we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker could consult the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country considerably affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "slayers".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, he could be conceived in full power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the citizen’s avenger) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power endure that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done a lot to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the network, since it would be like posting it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it’s also clear that, with current technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state has traveled by plane and made contact with one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents who travel discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has once again created a cable telegraph (telephone).
Videotapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digitals) only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques lead us back to the horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was secretly planned in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: France's turmoil in its pledges of funding
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked (called fast start or early) funding pledges made by developed countries have been honoured.
And the French dumps have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best cards to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The operation transparency was an appreciable result and was appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what “new and additional” means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken as its reference the year 2009: international financing is maintained and 150 million are added over three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references to the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of the year 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditures of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
Specifically, France’s total amount of aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while purporting to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funds.
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no norm and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to one euro donated.
Evidently, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to one euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it for yourself.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it manages to give the impression that it spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional", as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term minutiae in relation to the whole of the climate negotiations.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could push forward the debates on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have hope for the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingested 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a statistically significant value considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets of Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that usually consume a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which respect the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as the treats, were examined in the laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals individually are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is of concern," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil and intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in the food, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even breadstick or gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the slice of salmon was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these “pollutant cocktails” pose to the consumer “is probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
